<HL>
   Krieger Returns
   To Trading Role
   In Currencies
   ----
   By Michael R. Sesit
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   CPH
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
SECURITIES (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   Andrew J. Krieger, one of the biggest and most
controversial traders in global currency markets, is back in
the saddle.
   The 34-year-old currency options trader, who made about
$300 million in pretax foreign exchange earnings for Bankers
Trust Co. in 1987, is starting a new investment unit at
Capital Holding Corp., an insurance holding company based in
Louisville, Ky.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   His new job means that, for the first time in two years,
Mr. Krieger will manage enough money to be a major player
again in the $640 billion-a-day currency trading market, the
world's biggest. At Bankers Trust, and later at Soros
Management Co., a New York investment partnership, Mr.
Krieger was known for making trades so gigantic that
awestruck colleagues credited him with singlehandedly moving
currency exchange rates.
   The co-head of the new subsidiary, Capital Holding
Currency Advisors, is Jonathan M. Berg, a former Bankers
Trust managing director. Both Messrs. Krieger and Berg have
been named managing directors of the unit, which will be
based in Englewood Cliffs, N.J.
   The unit will trade mostly currency options for large
institutional clients, central banks and wealthy individuals,
as well as manage a small amount of Capital Holding's own
funds. An option gives its holder the right, but not the
obligation, to sell or purchase a security or, in this case,
currency at a specific price on or before a specific date.
   The new Capital Holding unit will offer investors three
basic products: an aggressive investment involving a high
degree of risk and potentially big rewards; a less-aggressive
trading strategy in which losses are limited to 11% to 15% a
year; and one in which investors are guaranteed the return of
their full initial investments at the end of a prescribed
period. Minimum investments will range from $100,000 to $5
million.
   Through Messrs. Krieger and Berg, who will be responsible
for the unit's marketing and sales, Capital Holding hopes to
increase its fee-based income, expand its expertise in
foreign markets, and diversify its portfolios, said Joseph M.
Tumbler, president of Capital Holding's accumulation and
investment group, which also manages Capital's portfolio.
   Last year, Capital Holding earned $219.7 million on
revenue of $2.5 billion. At year end, the company had about
$15 billion in assets.
   "When Jon {Berg} first told me we're going to Kentucky, I
said: `The horse races aren't for a while,'" Mr. Krieger
said. "When he said, `We're going to Capital Holding,' I
said, `What's Capital Holding?,' and Jon said: `Trust me.'"
The insurance company had been one of Mr. Berg's clients at
Bankers Trust.
   "Frankly," Mr. Krieger said, "they wanted to take a look
at me to see what kind of animal I was." Part of the process,
he said, included seating Mr. Krieger in a room "at the head
of a table with 13 people and grilling me for three hours on
everything from how I make trading decisions to how, when and
why I take profits and losses."
   Most traders and investors use currency options to hedge
an existing foreign-exchange position or to speculate on
currency movements with a small part of a large portfolio.
   By contrast, Mr. Krieger regards options as a separate
investment or asset category, and a conservative way to trade
currencies. Because currency option trading volume is heavy,
"The amount of money I can manage on a leveraged basis with
limited downside risk is very large," said Mr. Krieger, who
earned a reputation at Bankers Trust as a mover of markets
because of his large trades.
   The big risk in investing with options is that they will
expire before they can be exercised at a profit. In that
case, the investor loses all of the money initially paid to
purchase the option.
   But Mr. Krieger said that with his approach, "I don't have
to be right a whole lot, only about 25% to 30% of the time,
to yield substantial results." This is because options allow
an investor to bet on moves in large amounts of currencies
with relatively small premiums. A $100,000 investment in
options would normally control $30 million to $40 million of
foreign currency.
   He also said that during the course of a year, he
generally spends only 10% to 15% of all assets under
management to buy options. "So, even if I'm wrong on every
play, the downside is quite tolerable," Mr. Krieger said.
   Like his view of the options he trades, Mr. Krieger is
controversial. Unhappy with the $3 million, or 1%, bonus he
received for making the $300 million for Bankers Trust in
1987, he quit the following February. With a 5% bonus, which
is common for traders, Mr. Krieger would have netted $15
million. "I was very, very disappointed with the bonus on
principal, rather than the actual amount," he said. "It was
more money than I ever thought I'd need, but it wasn't fair."
He also needed a break from the intense world of trading, he
said.
   He later joined Soros but said he resigned after making
$45 million for the investment firm in 14 weeks. "My hours
were worse than they were at Bankers," he said. After a break
and travels to India, Mr. Krieger then set up his own firm;
its business will be transferred to the new Capital Holding
unit.
   He described the new unit as "a long-term venture; we have
a long-term commitment."
   Mr. Krieger's eclectic background includes a master's
degree and doctoral studies in Indian philosophy,
translations of Sanskrit texts, and a brief six-month career
as a professional tennis player. He always intended to make
his career in academia, but in the early 1980s, a combination
of marriage, a child and cutbacks in educational funding
forced him to reassess.
   "I was told by my adviser: `You're a great student, you
will be a great scholar, but you won't get a job until
someone dies in a plane crash,'" Mr. Krieger said. "Rather
than wishing someone's death, I decided to change fields."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
