<HL>
   Business Brief -- Equifax Inc.:
   Meetings Set for Holders
   To Vote on Stock Swap
</HL>
<DATE>
09/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EFX TCRD
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
INDUSTRIAL &amp; COMMERCIAL SERVICES, LEASING, CLEANING (ICS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Equifax Inc. said it and Telecredit Inc. set special
meetings of shareholders for Nov. 7 to vote on Equifax's
acquisition of Telecredit in a stock swap currently valued at
about $489 million.
   Equifax, an information-services concern in Atlanta, said
shareholders of record of the two companies as of Sept. 21
will be entitled to vote at the respective meetings.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The definitive agreement calls for Telecredit shareholders
to receive 2.69 shares of Equifax common for each share held.
In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Equifax
closed at $16.375 a share, down from $19.50 a share when the
deal was announced June 21. The exchange will bring the price
for Telecredit to $44.05 a share. However, Equifax has the
option, but not the obligation, of increasing the exchange
ratio to bring it to a $50-a-share value. Telecredit, a check
authorizer and credit processor based in Los Angeles,
conversely can terminate the transaction if the deal doesn't
fetch a bottom price of $50 a share.
   Both companies said that proxy materials will be sent to
holders about Sept. 21.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
