<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Indecency Then,
   Indecency Now
</HL>
<DATE>
09/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A19
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   The battle betwixt your editor, Robert L. Bartley, and
special prosecutor Lawrence W. Walsh on L. Gordon Crovitz's
remarks on the costs of the Iran-Contra prosecutions
(editorial page, Aug. 9) would be hilarious if the dispute
did not strike at the very foundation of our once-superb
political system. After reading Mr. Walsh's letter one can
only agree with attorney Joseph N. Welch's admonition to Sen.
Joseph McCarthy, June 9, 1954: "Let us not assassinate this
young lad further, Senator. You have done enough. Have you no
sense of decency, sir, at long last]"
   Richard L. Barkley
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Palo Alto, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
