<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   That Wasn't Ginger
   You Saw With Fred
</HL>
<DATE>
09/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A19
</SO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   In your Aug. 20 article "At Columbia, Comeback Is the Big
Production," you erroneously identify Fred Astaire's partner
in a vintage movie poster from "You'll Never Get Rich"
(Columbia, 1940) as Ginger Rogers. In fact, Mr. Astaire's
co-star in "You'll Never Get Rich" was Rita Hayworth. Mr.
Astaire's classic musicals with Ginger Rogers in 1933-1939
were made at the RKO Radio Studios.
   "You'll Never Get Rich," however, is notable not only for
being one of only two movies Astaire and Hayworth made
together (the other, again for Columbia, was "You Were Never
Lovelier"), but also for the wonderful supporting performance
by Robert Benchley and the rare cameo appearance of the Delta
Rhythm Boys. It is also a fine example of an overlooked
minigenre: the Hollywood movies taking a lighthearted look at
military life that were made between the inception of the
peacetime draft in 1940 and the Pearl Harbor attack, which
abruptly sobered the nation's outlook.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   L. Charles Landgraf
   London
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900912-0032
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900912-0032.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   UPI Closes Bureaus
   In 3 Western States
   In Restructuring Move
</HL>
<DATE>
09/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   FNNI ITCH
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- United Press International, as part of a
long-running restructuring of editorial operations, is
closing bureaus in three Western states and laying off some
full-time reporters.
   UPI spokesman Milt Capps confirmed published reports that
bureaus in New Mexico, Wyoming and Montana, many of them
operated by one person, would be closed. As part of the
restructuring, the news service has also given layoff notices
to one-person bureaus in Michigan and North Dakota, Mr. Capps
said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Capps wouldn't confirm the number of full-time
reporters or editors that have been or would be laid off. He
said that UPI at the same time is increasing its network of
stringers in those states and "exploring a number of joint
ventures at the state and regional level" with State News
Service and Financial World magazine.
   "Virtually every bureau in the system world-wide is
affected either by increases or decreases," Mr. Capps said.
The changes in the editorial operations began six weeks ago,
he said, and would "last a number of months."
   The news service is owned by Infotechnology Inc., which
also owns 47% of Financial News Network.
</TEXT>
