   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
09/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   A DEFICIT-REDUCTION PACT could be reached by today or
tomorrow, say White House and congressional budget
negotiators. Republicans and Democrats are converging on a
compromise that would raise taxes by about $130 billion over
five years, including an energy tax, a new luxury-goods levy
and higher taxes on alcoholic beverages.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Big Board approved a limited form of "off-hours"
trading for large investors that could begin later this year,
in a move that marks a step toward 24-hour stock trading.
   ---
   Drexel could face a $50 million Big Board fine, following
the exchange's request to bankruptcy court to initiate
disciplinary proceedings against the collapsed securities
firm.
   ---
   Salomon agreed to pay $83.8 million to the Department of
Energy to settle claims stemming from a probe of alleged
violations of the govern ment's crude-oil price controls.
   ---
   Chase Manhattan was forced by investors' uncertainties to
reset the rate on $200 million of subordinated notes to yield
13.017%, up from the previous rate of 9.66% and just shy of
the maximum permissible increase.
   ---
   The fund that insures bank deposits could require Treasury
assistance if a recession strikes, said the GAO. Some
lawmakers urged an other boost in bank insurance rates.
   ---
   First City Bancorp of Texas said it is considering seeking
one or more money-center banks as minority partners to shore
up the bank's finances and bolster its global standing.
   ---
   Philip Morris appointed William I. Campbell as president
and chief executive of its domestic tobacco subsidiary,
succeeding Ehud Houminer.
   ---
   A proposed accounting rule may be scaled back under
pressure from banks and accounting firms. The proposal,
involving debt issues, would make bank earnings more
volatile.
   ---
   Tenneco said its packaging unit is in talks to buy mills
and timberland from Georgia-Pacific for about $740 million,
extending the successful unit's pattern of acquisitions.
   ---
   ASK Computer agreed to buy software-maker Ingres in an
unusual four-way deal, in which ASK will use funds from stock
it will sell to Hewlett-Packard and GM's EDS unit.
   ---
   IBM will soon unveil several new computers that act as
network hubs, which will put it in direct rivalry with
Compaq, which controls the high end of that specialized
market.
   ---
   U.S. food-price inflation will be pushed up this year and
next by the Persian Gulf crisis, according to Agriculture
Department analysts.
   ---
   Texas Instruments is asking Japanese semiconductor makers
to pay higher royalties on a memory chip patent. The U.S.
company's stock soared on news of its demand.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 113,220,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2612.62, off 2.97; transportation 909.58, up 1.48; utilities
200.26, off 0.19.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3362.52, up
11.59.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.39, up 0.40; spot
index 129.67, up 0.58.
   Dollar: 140.30 yen, up 0.75; 1.5855 marks, up 0.0035.
